===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|comly}}, {{m|enm|cumly}}, {{m|enm|cumlich}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|cymlīc}}, {{m|ang|cȳmlīċ}} (compare Old English {{m|ang|cȳme||fine, exquisite}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*kūmiz||delicate}}), from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*kūmalīkaz||pitiful, dear}}. Cognate with Middle Dutch {{m|dum|komlick}}, {{m|dum|komelick}}, Middle High German {{m|gmh|komelīh}}, {{m|gmh|gomelīh}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈkʌmli/|lang=en}}
* {{audio|en-us-comely.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er|more}}

# {{lb|en|dated|of a person}} [[pleasing|Pleasing]] or [[attractive]] to the [[eye]].
#* South
#*: He that is '''comely''' when old and decrepit, surely was very beautiful when he was young.
#* Milton
#*: Not once perceive their foul disfigurement / But boast themselves more '''comely''' than before.
#* {{quote-text|year=1918|author={{w|Edgar Rice Burroughs}}|title=[[w:The Land That Time Forgot (novel)|The Land That Time Forgot]]|chapter=IX|passage=The chief's name was To-jo, and his household consisted of seven females and himself. These women were much more '''comely''', or rather less hideous than those of Tsa's people; one of them, even, was almost pretty, being less hairy and having a rather nice skin, with high coloring.}}
#* '''Jan 23, 2013''', Ian Pope, ''Modern Longbow Design & Toxophilus Longbow Design Refined by Ascham: A Voice from the Past''
#*: It should be whipped at the ends, '''comely''' in appearance.
# {{lb|en|archaic}} Suitable or becoming; [[proper]]; [[agreeable]].
#* Shakespeare
#*: This is a happier and more '''comely''' time / Than when these fellows ran about the streets, / Crying confusion.
#* Bible, Psalms cxlvii. 1
#*: It is good to sing praises unto our God; for it is pleasant; and praise is '''comely'''.

